==== We are germane to the topic;  We remove interference with production; secrecy restrictions are a restriction ====

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)David 4(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %) James David is a curator at the Smithsonian&amp;#39;s National Air and Space Museum. He is the author of Conducting Post-World War II National Security Research in Executive Branch Records: A Comprehensive Guide, published by Greenwood Press in 2001. The opinions expressed here do not necessarily represent the views of the National Air and Space Museum or the Smithsonian Institution. Progress and problems in declassifying U.S. government records James David National Air and Space Museum, Smithsonian Institution, Washington, DC 20560, USA Available online 11 November 2004.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)There have been three(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) distinct and (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)**__separate categories of information that have been classified__**(%%)**__ __**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)over the years. The first is National Security Information (NSI). The current system of classification of NSI is set forth in E.O. 13292, signed by President Bush in March 2003. It is the latest in a series of executive orders on NSI that date back to World War II. In general conformance with its predecessors, E.O. 13292 preserves the classification of information under predecessor orders and mandates that newly created information in eight broad areas be classified, ranging from “military plans, weapons systems, or operations” to “scientific, technological, or economic matters relating to the national security, which includes defense against transnational terrorism.” The records containing the information are marked Top Secret, Secret, or Confidential, depending on the damage to national security reasonably expected to occur from its unauthorized disclosure. The order continues the provisions of E.O. 12958 that require personnel classifying information to set a date or event within twenty-five years for the automatic declassification of that information. If no such date or event can be determined, the information can be classified between ten and twenty-five years. Agencies can extend the duration of classification under certain circumstances.3 The second category of classified information is that generally relating to nuclear weapons and atomicenergy. The original authority in this area was the AtomicEnergyAct of 1946, which was superseded by (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)**__the Atomic Energy Act of 1954__**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). Among other things, this statute (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)**__mandates information be classified__**(%%)**__ __**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)as Restricted Data (RD) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)**__if it concerns __**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)((% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)1) the design or manufacture of atomic weapons, (2) the (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)**__production of __**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)special (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)**__nuclear materials, __**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)(3) nuclear propulsion of aircraft, spacecraft, and naval vessels. It also requires information be classified as Formerly Restricted Data (FRD) if it concerns the military utilization of nuclear weapons.4 (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)**__Any information that is classified as RD or FRD is also classified as NSI, but not vice versa__**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) The third category is Sensitive Compartmented Information (SCI), which is information “concerning or derived from intelligence sources, methods, or analytical processes, which is required to be handled with formal access controls established by the Director of Central Intelligence.”5 It is designated by codewords representing information in a broad area and additional codewords representing more specific types of information under each general area. The codeword themselves are classified, and only in recent years have a few been declassified (for example, “RUFF” which covers imagery from certain overhead platforms). Just as with RD and FRD, any information classified as SCI is also classified as NSI, but not vice versa.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
And this restriction is on production

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Von Mises Inst. (http:~/~/mises.org/humanaction/chap29sec1.asp)

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Restriction of production means(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)that the (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)government(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)either (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)forbids or makes more difficult(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)or more expensive the (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)production(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), transportation, or distribution of definite articles, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)or the(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)application(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)of definite modes (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)of (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)productio(%%)n(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), transportation, or distribution. The authority thus eliminates some of the means available for the satisfaction of human wants.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 12pt; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)The effect of(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)its (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)interference is(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)that (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)people are prevented from using their knowledge (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)and abilities, their (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)labor and (%%)their (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)material means of production in the way (%%)in (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)which (%%)they(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)would earn the highest returns(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) and satisfy their needs as much as possible. Such interference makes people poorer and less(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) satisfied.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
Our counter interp is that we don&amp;#39;t have to roleplay as the USFG, as long as we provide a method for how we interact with the law, and that method is testable.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
We focus on the everydayness of law, specifically the use of peoples tribunals to scrutinize the USFG secrecy restrictions as enacted through our daily behavior, outside formal legal institutions.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 13pt; background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)Berman 05(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %)(Paul Schiff.   Professor, University of Connecticut School of Law.  : From International Law to Law and Globalization.  Columbia Journal of Transnational Law)

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %) 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7pt; &amp;#34; %)In considering legal consciousness, moreover, we must remember that(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7pt; font-family: Arial; &amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)law is not simply(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7pt; &amp;#34; %) the official texts of treaties, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)judicial opinions, and legislative acts(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7pt; &amp;#34; %) that embody formal legal rules, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)nor(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7pt; &amp;#34; %) is it just the (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)formal legal institutions(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7pt; &amp;#34; %) of courts, lawyers and police. Accordingly, instead of focusing solely on laws and official legal actors, legal consciousness research examines the wide variety of &amp;#34;quasi-legal&amp;#34; discourses, such as abstract (and often intuitive) ideas of street justice, due process, civil disobedience, retribution, deterrence, and rights, all of which are frequently invoked in public discussions and dinner-table conversations alike. (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7pt; &amp;#34; %)Finally, the study of legal consciousness also makes clear that(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7pt; font-family: Arial; &amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7pt; &amp;#34; %)the relationship between law and culture is not unidirectional. While legal categories do shape broader social discourse, at the same time (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)law talk, diffused throughout society, becomes a source of alternative conceptions of law(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %): (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)Legality operates through social life as persons(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7pt; &amp;#34; %) and groups deliberately interpret and (% style=&amp;#34;background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)invoke law&amp;#39;s language(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %),(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7pt; &amp;#34; %) authority, and procedures (% style=&amp;#34;background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)to organize their lives(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7pt; &amp;#34; %) and manage their relationships. In short, the commonplace operation of (% style=&amp;#34;background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)law in daily life makes us all legal agents(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7pt; &amp;#34; %) insofar as (% style=&amp;#34;background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)we actively make law, even when no formal legal agent is involved(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7pt; &amp;#34; %). This focus on law in everyday life n30 recognizes that people interpret their experiences by drawing on a collaboration of law and other social structures. These interpretations may be widely varied and will, of course, depend in part on each person&amp;#39;s social class, previous contact with the law, and political standing. Nevertheless, legal consciousness constitutes an ongoing interaction between official norms as embodied in the common sense categories of daily life and each individual&amp;#39;s ongoing participation in the process of constructing legality. Accordingly, legal consciousness includes the ways in which (% style=&amp;#34;background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)individuals(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7pt; &amp;#34; %) themselves deploy, transform, or (% style=&amp;#34;background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)subvert official legal understandings and thereby &amp;#34;construct&amp;#34; law on the ground(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7pt; &amp;#34; %). We all always take part in the construction of legal consciousness, even as we are also inevitably affected by the legal categories of the social structures around us.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

==== 2). The topical demand is one that subjects debaters to the ultimate sovrign of the “USFG” in service to transnational capitalism. We can never have our aff through the lens of the USFg because of the way that always already situates our response ====

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Kato, 2011(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6.0pt;mso-font-kerning:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)(Masahide T, professor of ethnic studies at the University of Hawaii, famous Hawaiian, baller, exposes the ontopolitical subjective gaze, interview with Christopher Spurlock, kdebate.com/kato.html ~\~\stroud)

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Kato: I am often asked to comment on high school debate topics. But every time I try to work on it, I encounter a tremendous difficulty in answering the question. And I apologize for those debaters who asked me the debate topic and never got my answer. I began to write a lengthy answer but I still haven’t been able to finish it. Hopefully one day I can finish it up and share with your readers. The hardest part is (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)the grammar of the topic(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)The “USFG” is always and already the sovereign subject that takes a certain action(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) or actions that may result in a positive or negative impact upon the US, other nation states, regions, and the planet (and perhaps beyond this planet in this case). (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)But my question is what if the USFG is simply an effect of the biopolitical network(%%) that coordinates seemingly unrelated flows of capital, goods, information, services, labor, waste, etc (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)for the profit maximization of transitional conglomerates. The popular will or popular sovereignty that had made the USFG as a collective representative of the constitutional subject may no longer be a valid grammar to capture the biopolitical regime of globalization(%%).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) If seen from this angle, one can recognize how the (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)space exploration originates in the shift of philosophy over the role of the nation state in the so-called neo-liberal economy(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %). (Foucault’s Birth of Biopolitics will be very useful here) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)The development of space exploration sets the tone of hyper-Keynesian policy where the public investment is not geared to the growth of national wealth but to the growth of transnational conglomerates as a form of corporate subsidies. The current US debt crisis is a cumulative result of this hyper-Keynesianism(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %). As such if the space program is to survive, I suspect that it won’t be under the auspices of USFG but the transnational conglomerates.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
3). More organic approaches to what it means to interact with the government are better for policy making, and it is a way to ensure that the development of science and technology end up serving the interest of the people and not the technobureautcrats and ceos of power companies.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
**Adams 2003**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:5.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt&amp;#34; %)(Jason, The Evergreen State College, POPULAR DEFENSE IN THE EMPIRE OF SPEED: PAUL VIRILIO AND THE PHENOMENOLOGY OF THE POLITICAL BODY. THESIS SUBMITTED IN PARTIAL FULFILLMENT OF THE REQUIREMENTS FOR THE DEGREE OF MASTER OF ARTS - In the Department Of Political Science - SIMON FRASER UNIVERSITY - November 2003)(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 5pt; &amp;#34; %) 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %)Thus we can see that for Virilio for (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)as long as technology has been allowed to become ever more autonomous, the (%%)//deliberative basis//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) on which politics rests has been undermined since it has exempted (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)what is arguably(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) the most important element of public administration from consideration.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)In order for the political to prevail over the technical then, (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)//the metadesign of society//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) that results from the introduction of technique (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)//must be subjected to open and sustained debate and decision-making//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) processes (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)which(%%) (%%)//directly (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)involve the populations affected by them//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %).I5 If this were to take place, he argues, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)the(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) likely (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)//result would be the scaling back of large-scale authoritarian technologies such as nuclear power//(%%)// //(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)and the emergence of small-scale democratic technologies such as wind power(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %), which is why (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)it should (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)not (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)be taken from his (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)pessimism about the present(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %) that he wants to turn back the clock to &amp;#39;Year Zero&amp;#39;, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)but rather (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)that (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 12pt; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)he would prefer (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)to wait and see what might appear within the context of a society in which science and technology are transformed so as to serve the interest of the public rather than that of the elites who go to such great lengths to protect their autonomy(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %)I6It is for this reason that it is rather difficult to place him within a particular tradition of technological thought since he is both negative about the short term future of technology and positive about its long term potentiality at one and the same time. While on the one hand he agrees with Ellul that the instrumental logic of technology as we know it today has become so pervasive that ours is more appropriately described as a &amp;#39;technological society&amp;#39; than as a capitalist society, since even non-capitalist societies such as the Soviet Union held that &amp;#39;communism is socialism plus electricity&amp;#39; and were thus in many way of a piece with our own, on the other hand he also takes from Heidegger that (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)&amp;#34;we must take hold of the riddle of technology and lay it on the table (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)as the ancient philosophers and scientists put the riddle of Nature out in the open.. .we must politicize speed, whether it be the metabolic speed (the speed of the living being, of reflexes) or technological speed. We must(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %) politicize speed, because we are both: we are moved, and we&amp;#39;move(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %). To drive is also to be driven&amp;#34;.In order to accomplish this, his suggestion is that(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)citizens should immediately demand meetings with the engineers and technicians in order to really discuss (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)both the positive and(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)the (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)negative(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)implications of what is being brought into existence today(%%), just as the developers of the railway system throughout Europe got together in Brussels in 1888 and came up with the &amp;#39;block system&amp;#39; to prevent accidents as a result. (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %)What was unique in that instance, and what is unheard of today, as Virilio notes, is that (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)&amp;#34;the starting point of the discussion in Brussels was on the negative, on what did not function(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Contact switches and signals were devised, and these became the basis of a very sophisticated form of data management(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). But why are there no conferences nowadays on the damaging consequences of unemployment? On the wrong turns taken by urbanism? On the obverse side of technical progress?&amp;#34;

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

==== Impact turn.  They are the only risk of producing the thoughtless Eichmann their Miller evidence indicts.  Our indirection is key to solve.  ====

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 13pt; font-family: Calibri; &amp;#34; %)**Spurlock and Spanos.  2011.  “Interview Questions”.  Spurlock is a debate coach at the University of Texas at San Antonio.  William V. Spanos is professor emeritus of literature at the University of Binghamton, author and World War II veteran.  Accessed from: (% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)http:~~/~~/www.kdebate.com/spanos.htmlurl:http://www.kdebate.com/spanos.html(%%) – M.E.**

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; font-family: Calibri; &amp;#34; %)The danger of being a total insider is that the eye of such a person becomes blind to alternative possibilities.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri; &amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri; background: yellow&amp;#34; %)**__The extreme manifestation of this being at one with the system, of remaining inside the frame,__**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; font-family: Calibri; &amp;#34; %) as it were, (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri; background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)**__is, as__**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri; &amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; font-family: Calibri; &amp;#34; %)Hannah(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri; &amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri; background: yellow&amp;#34; %)**__Arendt__**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; font-family: Calibri; &amp;#34; %),(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri; &amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; font-family: Calibri; &amp;#34; %)decisively(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri; &amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri; background: yellow&amp;#34; %)**__demonstrated__**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri; &amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; font-family: Calibri; &amp;#34; %)long ago,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri; background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)**__ Adolph Eichmann.__**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri; &amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; font-family: Calibri; &amp;#34; %)That&amp;#39;s why she and Said, among many poststructuralists, believed that to be an authentic intellectual -(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri; background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)**__-to see what disinterested inquiry can&amp;#39;t see~-~- one has to be an exile (or a pariah) from a homeland-__**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; font-family: Calibri; &amp;#34; %)- one who is both apart of and apart from the dominant culture. Unlike Socrates, for example, Hippias, Socrates&amp;#39; interlocutor in the dialogue &amp;#34;Hippias Major&amp;#34; (he is, for Arendt, the model for Eichmann), is at one with himself. When he goes home at night &amp;#34;he remains one.&amp;#34; He is, in other words, incapable of thinking. When Socrates, the exilic consciousness, goes home, on the other hand, he is not alone; he is &amp;#34;by himself.&amp;#34; He is two-in-one. He has to face this other self. He has to think. Insofar as its logic is faithfully pursued,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri; background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)**__ the framework of the debate system, __**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; font-family: Calibri; &amp;#34; %)to use your quite appropriate initial language, (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri; background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)**__does__**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; font-family: Calibri; &amp;#34; %), indeed, (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri; background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)**__produce horrifically thoughtless Eichmanns,__**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri; &amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; font-family: Calibri; &amp;#34; %)which is to say,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri; background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)**__ a political class whose thinking, whether it&amp;#39;s called Republican or Democratic, is thoughtless in that it is totally separated from and indifferent to the existential realities of the world it is representing.__**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; font-family: Calibri; &amp;#34; %) It&amp;#39;s no accident, in my mind, that those who govern us in America ~-~-our alleged representatives, whether Republican, Neo-Con, or Democrat~-~- constitute such a &amp;#34;political class.&amp;#34; This governing class has, in large part, their origins, in a preparatoary relay consisting of the high school and college debate circuit, political science departments, and the law profession. The moral of this story is that the debate world needs more outsiders ~-~- or, rather, inside outsiders ~-~- if its ultimate purpose is to prepare young people to change the world rather than to reproduce it.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; %)
