(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
//This is bad education – it locks us into what Spanos calls the “problematic” where we&amp;#39;re enacting the same formulaic CP and Politics debate every round, blind to the outcome of our framing or the violence it allows. Spanos explains;//

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %)One could supplement Ohmann’s damning critical analysis of (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %)the “can do” language and(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %) the (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %)deeply inscribed panoptic structure of(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %) this enormous archive of memoranda by pointing to their unerring and mind-numbing sameness: (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %)their(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)systematic reliance on the quantitative measure, the abstracting and reductive cliché, the euphemisms, the short-hand structure of the sentences(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; background-color: lime; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)—(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background-color: lime; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)what Eichmann called the “appropriate telegraphic style” in speaking of the(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; &amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %)“monthly reports” on the progress of the (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; &amp;#34; %)“(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background-color: lime; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)Final Solution(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; &amp;#34; %)”(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %) he sent to the Reichsführer-SS Heinrich Himmler7—(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background-color: lime; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)and(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %), subsuming these,(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; &amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background-color: lime; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)the “problem-solving” model. This model, like(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %)the “over-sight” or “super-vision” of(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)the(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %)capitalist(%%) “(% style=&amp;#34;background: lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)problematic(%%)” (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %)brilliantly(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %) analyzed by(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %) Louis (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %)Althusser(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %) in “From Capital to Marx’s Philosophy(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %),” (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)blinds the willful inquirer to any differential reality that would contradict and thus remain an obstacle to the end he/she desires(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %)from the beginning:(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)in this case, “the suffering of the Vietnamese,” which “did not impinge on the consciousness of the policy makers(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background-color: lime; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %),” that is, “//had virtually no existence for them//”(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; &amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %)(my emphasis). One could also mark the obliteration of conscience, which Arendt over-determines in her devastating analysis of Eichmann’s language, achieved in these Pentagon memoranda by the insistent identification of the realities instigating it as a neurosis—the “‘French defeat’ and ‘Korean syndromes,’” as well as pointing to the genealogy of what, in the aftermath of the war under the massive campaign of the American government and the culture industry to “forget Vietnam” in the name of resuming its mission in the world’s wilderness (specifically the Middle East), came to be called “the Vietnam syndrome.” But, for the purpose on my argument, I want to underscore what Ohmann long ago noted at the outset of his criticism, but did not adequately amplify about the “agents” of these memoranda.(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; &amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background-color: lime; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)This deadly(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; &amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %)cliché-ridden and euphemistic “telegraphic(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %)”(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)language(%%), whose superficiality(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %)—is it inappropriate to call this symptom of these documents “banality”?—(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %)lent itself to the pervasive routinization of a murderous indiscriminate violence against America’s demonized “Others,” is not(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %), as it is in a totalitarian society, (%%)that of a militarist mentality. It (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)is(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %), (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %)rather(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %), (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background-color: lime; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)the language of civilians, precisely those “ordinary” Americans (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %)who exist in democracies to protect society from the juggernaut mentality of the militaristic mind.

