// //

==== Secrecy within science doesn’t hold research to a high enough standard, and promotes “bad” scientific research methods. ====

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %) 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Schrange 09(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)Secrecy in science is a corrosive force, The writer researches the economics of innovation and technology transfer at MIT and is a visiting researcher at London&amp;#39;s Imperial College(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶ ¶ ¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)Schrage, Michael. FT.com (Nov 27, 2009)., http:~/~/pus.sagepub.com/content/1/3/281.short

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %) 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)With no disrespect to sausages and laws, Bismarck&amp;#39;s most famous aphorism clearly requires updating. &amp;#34;(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Scientific research&amp;#34; is bidding furiously to make the global shortlist of things one should not see being made.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Understandably so. Sciences at the cutting edge of statistics and public policy can make blood sports seem genteel. Scientists aggressively promoting pet hypotheses often relish the opportunity to marginalise and neutralise rival theories and exponents.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) The malice, mischief and Machiavellian manoeuvrings revealed in the illegally hacked megabytes of emails from the University of East Anglia&amp;#39;s prestigious Climate Research Unit, for example, offers a useful paradigm of contemporary scientific conflict. Science may be objective; scientists emphatically are not. This episode illustrates what too many universities, professional societies, and research funders have irresponsibly allowed their scientists to become. Shame on them all.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) The source of that shame is a toxic mix of institutional laziness and complacency. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Too many scientists in (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)academia, industry and government (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)are allowed to get away with concealing or withholding vital information about their data, research methodologies and results(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) That is unacceptable and must change.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Only recently in America, for example, have academic pharmaceutical researchers been required to disclose certain financial conflicts of interest they might have(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %). On issues of the greatest importance for public policy, science researchers less transparent than they should be. (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)That behaviour undermines science, policy and public trust(%%).¶ Dubbed &amp;#34;climate-gate&amp;#34; by global warming sceptics, the most outrageous East Anglia email excerpts appear to suggest respected scientists misleadingly manipulated data and suppressed legitimate argument in peer-reviewed journals.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) These claims are forcefully denied, but the correspondents do little to enhance confidence in either the integrity or the professionalism of the university&amp;#39;s climatologists. What is more, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)there are no denials around the researchers&amp;#39; repeated efforts to avoid meaningful compliance with several requests under the UK Freedom of Information Act to gain access to their working methods. Indeed, researchers were asked to delete and destroy emails.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Secrecy, not privacy, is at the rotten heart of this bad behavior by ostensibly good scientists.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Why should research funding institutions and taxpayers fund scientists who deliberately delay, obfuscate and deny open access to their research? (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Why should scientific journals publish peer-reviewed research where the submitting scientists have not made every reasonable effort to make their work - from raw data to sophisticated computer simulations - as transparent and accessible as possible? (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Why should responsible policymakers in America(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %), Europe, Asia and Latin America (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)make decisions affecting people&amp;#39;s(%%) health, wealth and (% style=&amp;#34;background: lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)future based on(%%) opaque and (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)inaccessible science?(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) They should not. The issue here is not about good or bad science, it is about insisting that scientists and their work be open and transparent enough so that research can be effectively reviewed by broader communities of interest. (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Open science minimises the likelihood and consequences of bad science(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Debilitating and even fatal side-effects of new drugs might have been detected sooner if pharmaceutical companies had been compelled to share data on all the trials they ran, not just favourable ones. Similarly, the flawed and successfully overturned 1999 child murder conviction of Sally Clark might never have occurred if the statistical errors made by expert witness pediatrician Sir Roy Meadow had been questioned earlier(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %). Data withholding played a distortive and destructive role in the cold fusion frenzy 20 years ago, when two scientists announced they had produced energy by cold fusion, only to be widely and quickly denounced by the scienitific community(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). Concealment and secrecy invites mischief; too many scientists seeking influence accept the invitation.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Achieving this (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)is simple and inexpensive(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) It is not done by more rigorous enforcement of the Freedom of Information Act, although that would help. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)It (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)comes from branding &amp;#34;openness&amp;#34; into every link of the scientific research value (%%)chain. Public or tax-deductible research funding should be contingent upon maximum transparency.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Scientists and affiliated institutions that will not make the research process as transparent as the end result will be asked to return the money or risk denial of future funds. University accreditation should be contingent not just upon faculty research and publication but by demonstrating policies and practices that champion data sharing. Professional societies and journals should make data sharing a condition of membership and publication. Researchers must be pushed to be more open at every step of their process.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) The Royal Society not only makes data sharing a precondition of publication, it provides up to 10 megabytes of free space for supplementary data on its website. Unfortunately, too many scientific societies and publishers are less than rigorous or insistent about openness. Strip them of their tax-deductible status. Make opennes a condition of tax advantage. Of course commercial and proprietary issues can influence the manner of data sharing and transparency. But the East Anglia emails represent an individual and institutional imperative to err on the side of minimal disclosure even as researchers sought to maximise the academic and political impact of their work. That is perverse.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Public interest suggests scientists and their sponsoring institutions be made as legally, financially, professionally and ethically as uncomfortable as possible about concealing and withholding relevant research information.(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)If the University of East Anglia had been sharing more of its data and the computer models and statistical simulations running that data, the email hack would have been much ado about nothing.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) When doing important research about the potential future of the planet, scientists should have nothing to hide. Their obligation to the truth is an obligation to openness.</headline></objectSummary><objectSummary><link rel="http://www.xwiki.org/rel/object" href="http://opencaselist.paperlessdebate.com/xwiki/rest/wikis/opencaselist/spaces/Texas-San%20Antonio/pages/nerison-stroud%20Aff/objects/Admin.EntryClass/3"/><link rel="http://www.xwiki.org/rel/properties" href="http://opencaselist.paperlessdebate.com/xwiki/rest/wikis/opencaselist/spaces/Texas-San%20Antonio/pages/nerison-stroud%20Aff/objects/Admin.EntryClass/3/properties"/><id>opencaselist:Texas-San Antonio.nerison-stroud Aff:b5404017-ce59-49f4-b22c-82ab5b5a4e53</id><guid>b5404017-ce59-49f4-b22c-82ab5b5a4e53</guid><pageId>opencaselist:Texas-San Antonio.nerison-stroud Aff</pageId><wiki>opencaselist</wiki><space>Texas-San Antonio</space><pageName>nerison-stroud Aff</pageName><className>Admin.EntryClass</className><number>3</number><headline>== 2ac; CAP ==&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
We win uniqueness; capitalism has a hand in nuclear decisions and is insulated from oversight.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
Our 1ac outlines how dangers of Japanese reactors were well known to the public, politicians, and engineers, but the Tokyo Electric Power Company had complete sovereignty over the plant. Post meltdown, no one from the company was held responsible for what our Onishi and Fackler ev indicates was, “murder of its own people”.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
The same situation exists in the US; Galison says(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) “Under the Atomic Energy Acts…all nuclear information is secret.” (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %)And Masco explains this extends to “the banal details of managing a large government bureaucracy” and the “health and environmental effects of nuclear production”. The AEA exempts nuclear power from environmental or other oversight, and EPA is helpless to control nuclear waste, as per our Trento ev.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %) &#xD;
&#xD;
==== ALT: ====&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %)The only way you should evaluate solvency for cap must be premised on which strat best dissipates this monopoly on nuclear info/decisions, because if the squo nuclear framework is left intact, privatized nuclear power will continue to remain unaccountable to anyone and will risk the well being of is constituents with or without their consent.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
-The alt is in a double bind; either, the alt would eventually challenge nuclear expertism/secrecy and the links to the squo are better then the links to the aff, or they leave secrecy intact and can’t solve the K because;&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
1). Extend Kinsella 11; secrecy turns members of the nuclear institutional system into docile citizens who blindly replicate that order without the agency or responsibility to challenge and criticize it.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
This control extends to the entire polis because nuclear secrecy necessitates that nuclear power keep “non-experts” from even accessing nuclear decisions. &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
2). extend the last Kinsella card, it said this expert rationality, in privatizing nuclear debates that involve the fate of the global commons, then it can control and manage all other public policy debates.&#xD;
&#xD;
==== 3).  Current Nuclear discourse freezes all social possibilities. ====&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Kinsella 11(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %) One Hundred Years of Nuclear Discourse: Four Master Themes and Their Implications for Environmental Communication William J. Kinsella PhD, Associate Professor At North Carolina State University, Director of the University&amp;#39;s interdisciplinary program in Science, U.S. Fulbright Scholar at the Institute for Nuclear Energy and Energy Systems, University of Stuttgart, Germany. President of the National Communication Association’s Environmental Communication Division during 2009-2010.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Although (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)the material catastrophe (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)envisioned by Einstein has not (yet) occurred, arguably it (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)bas been replaced by a social and political catastrophe(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), a catastrophe of public discourse. In an influential essay that helped inaugurate the &amp;#34;nuclear criticism&amp;#34; project ofthe mid-1980s (cf. Norris, 1994), Derrida (1984) suggested that (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)the prospect of nuclear annihilation &amp;#34;through all the techno-scientific inventiveness (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)that it (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)motivates, structures (%%)not only the army, diplomacy, politics, but(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) the whole of the human socius(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)&amp;#34; (p. 23). In a Burkean reading of Derrida, consistent 58 KINSELLA with the preceding discussion of nuclear mystery, Williams (1989) suggested that the (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)nuclear threat has(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)acquired the status(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)of a transcendental signified, a value or (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)meaning that stands outside language.(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)As an overarching presence beyond the hmits of linguistic representation, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)that threat appears (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)mysterious and (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)self-generating. Such an ontological or theological absolute can neither be changed nor ignored; it appears as if our only available response is to submit to its (%%)potent (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)disciplinary effects(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Examining a wide range of popular cultural texts from tbe Cold War era, Nadel (1995) demonstrated how (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)these(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)disciplinary effects (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)extended well beyond the(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)(explicitly) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)nuclear domain(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). Although the U.S. geopolitical strategy of &amp;#34;containment&amp;#34; through nuclear threat was directed at the Soviet Union, it motivated a parallel domestic containment of individual identities, social roles, cultural expression, and political discourse. Under the nuclear sign, operationalized as a binary opposition between the superpowers, the general population internalized behavioral and discursive boundaries modeled in countless mass media messages and in everyday social interaction. Thus, writing almost 4 decades after Einstein at an advanced stage ofthe Cold War, Baudrillard (1983) displayed an optimism regarding our basic survival but a pessimism regarding tbe conditions of tbat survival. Although his comment was directed at the Cold War deterrence regime, it now seems eerily relevant to emerging concerns about social control in an era marked by new fears of nuclear proliferation and terrorism: It isn&amp;#39;t that the direct menace of atomic destruction paralyzes our lives....Deterrence excludes war—the antiquated violence of exploding systems. Deterrence is the neutral, implosive violence of metastable or involving systems. The risk of nuclear atomization only serves as a pretext... to the installation of a universal system of security, linkup, and control whose deterrent effect does not aim for atomic clash at all... but really the much larger probability of any real event, of anything which could disturb the general system and upset the balance. The balance of terror is the terror of balance, (pp. 59-60) Ironically appropriating a term from nuclear weapons design, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Baudrillard (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)(1994) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)described an &amp;#34;implosion&amp;#34; of culture and politics around a narrow range of possibilities. (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)The threat of material annihilation is transformed into a potent discursive annihilation encompassing public speech, cultural expression, and political process, as society&amp;#39;s efforts are focused on sustaining the precarious nuclear order.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
==== (% style=&amp;#34;font-weight:normal;mso-bidi-font-weight:bold&amp;#34; %) 4). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; %)Secrecy reinforces American political paranoia, which means the government can stop the rev anytime they want by deeming it a danger to national security.(%%) ====&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Dean 11 (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)Robert Dean, Associate Professor of History at Eastern Washington University Introduction: Cultures of Secrecy in Postwar America, the journal for the society of historians of foreign relations, Issue Diplomatic History, Volume 35, Issue 4, pages 611–613, September 2011&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)State secrecy creates an inevitable tension between the fundamental cultural(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) values and institutions of a democracy and the practices of the government.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) Since the onset of the Cold War era, the United States has seen a huge growth(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) in secret “national security” bureaucracies(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) designed to provide the executive(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) branch with intelligence concerning the intentions and capabilities of actual or(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) potential enemies, and to provide the capacity to wage covert campaigns against(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) those deemed to pose a threat to U.S. security. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)As American imperial ambitions(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)¶(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)and institutions (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)grew, (%%)the nature of (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)“threats to national security” became an(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) ever-expanding category.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Largely unbeknownst to the American public, at least(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) initially, and with the complicity of a Congress unwilling to inquire very deeply(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) into the actions of an increasingly imperial presidency, the CIA and other secret(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) bureaucracies repeatedly intervened to overthrow (or attempted to overthrow)(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) third world governments, conducted campaigns of sabotage and psychological(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) warfare, attempted to assassinate foreign leaders, abetted authoritarian regimes(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) in the murderous repression of their own people, and developed and disseminated techniques of “no-touch” torture. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)The (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)newly vigorous (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)national security(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) state (%%)rapidly (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)insinuated itself into a range of civilian institutions. (%%)Technical,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) scientiﬁc, and social science researchers, showered with federal funding, often(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) embraced the new culture of secrecy and “security(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %).”(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) In highly classiﬁed national(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) security memoranda, and other policy and doctrine, the executive branch arrogated to itself sweepingly broad powers to conduct policy in secret on behalf of(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) the governed but without the consent of the governed.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) A culture of (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)anticommunism justiﬁed and propelled the growth of this(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) massive institutionalization of militarized secrecy. The production and control(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) of national security secrets also shaped contests over power within and among(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) government agencies and among rivals for political power in Washington. The(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) apparent existential danger posed by an “expansionist” nuclear-armed imperial(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) rival combined(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) with the fear generated by the presence of a small sect of(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Communists and ideological sympathizers within American borders to (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)produce(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) a virulent Red Scare.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) The existence of (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)a genuine, if already disabled, Soviet espionage network (%%)in(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) the wartime United States seemed to (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)lend credence to the alarmist fulminations(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) of counter subversives (%%)of all stripes. (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)The Red Scare (%%)(and the closely related(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) Lavender Scare(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)) saw a profound assault on civil liberties and constitutional(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) protections of due process, largely orchestrated by the Right, (%%)and (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)which targeted those(%%) deemed to be (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)politically subversive (%%)or(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) otherwise construed as a “security(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) threat.” The resulting loyalty-security inquisition went after left-leaning(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Hollywood ﬁgures, academics and teachers, labor unions, State Department(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) diplomats, and even CIA employees. Blacklists, ritual confession and public(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) humiliation, and career destroying “separation” from the State Department and(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) other agencies, were tools central to this manifestation of the “paranoid style” of(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) American politics.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) The (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)institutionalization of Cold War secrecy (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)and the partisan posturing(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) surrounding national security in the atomic age (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)produced a cultural obsession(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) (%%)that played out in a variety of ways. (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)The seeming dangers to the U(%%)nited (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)S(%%)tates(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)posed by concealed political or sexual identities generated a kind of collective(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) hysteria,(%%) a “panic on the Potomac,” (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)that drove the counter subversion and(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) counter perversion crusade. (%%)Conspiracy became a central trope in the discourse(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) of the politically disaffected or those out of power seeking to destroy the(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) legitimacy of their opponents. The rapidly growing peacetime culture of secrecy(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) in Washington lent plausibility to demagogic assertions of “immense” conspiracies undermining America from within. With large parts of the foreign policy(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) bureaucracy operating entirely outside the scrutiny of the public, and with black(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) budgets and other mechanisms to avoid any effective oversight by Congress,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) citizens willing to do so could easily imagine cabals of subversive elites craftily(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) selling out the United States in the Manichean struggle against implacable(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) enemies.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) While (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)aspects of this kind of distrust (%%)have deep historical roots (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)in (%%)American(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) political culture(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %),(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background: lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)the decades of the Cold War and the subsequent “war on(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) terror(%%)” that followed (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)saw an entrenchment of these patterns(%%).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) The assassination(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) of a president, the debacle of Vietnam, and its attendant deceptions set the stage(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) for the cultural and political shocks of the 1970s. The revelations of the Pentagon Papers demonstrated the bad faith of several administrations and, for(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) many on the Left, illustrated the danger of wars of choice managed covertly by(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) elites protected by all-encompassing schemes of national security classiﬁcation.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Richard Nixon discredited the presidency itself by conducting a vendetta against(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Daniel Ellsberg, who took it upon himself to declassify a secret history of the(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) American intervention in Vietnam and provide it to the press. Employing “black(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) ops” performed by erstwhile CIA and FBI ﬁgures and anti-Castro mercenaries(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) associated with the failed Bay of Pigs invasion, Nixon set off a chain of events leading to the Watergate scandal and forced resignation to avoid an impeachment trial. The subsequent hearings of the Church and Pike Committees aired(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) some of the covert operations of the CIA, the “family jewels,” including illegal(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) domestic spying on American citizens. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)The defense of national security took on(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)¶(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) new cultural meanings, often producing a deep suspicion of (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)the (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)motives and(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) concealed practices of the state(%%).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) Cultures of secrecy exist in perpetual tension with a culture of democratic(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) openness. We live in a society that boasts of its commitment to human freedom(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) and dignity, yet culturally constructed “imperatives” of national security have been used to justify the (temporarily) secret use of “extraordinary rendition,” an(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) ofﬁcial euphemism for subcontracting torture in the so-called war on terror.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) The American public has largely acquiesced in the use of torture by American(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) intelligence agencies in the failed imperial wars in Afghanistan and Iraq(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). The(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) so-called Patriot Act of 2001 was rushed into law by congressional legislators,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) few of whom had read the document. Again justiﬁed by the imperatives of(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) national security, the act circumvented many of the constitutional protections(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) for basic civil liberties, putting the tools of a surveillance state in the hands of(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) federal secret policemen.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Rife with contradiction, pervasive government secrecy in a democracy presents historians with a wide range of questions about processes of cultural(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) transformation that accompany the massive institutionalization of covert action,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) surveillance of perceived foreign and domestic enemies, and the accompanying(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) emergence of widespread suspicion concerning the purposes and morality of the(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) “secret government(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %).(%%)”(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) This forum was conceived as an initial step toward developing different strands of historical inquiry focused on “cultures of secrecy” in(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) the postwar United States. The essays that follow are the result of an openended request to three talented scholars to develop this theme in relation to(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) their own historical concerns.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
