(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Heron and Smith 6(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) critical masses and critical choices; evolving public opinion on nuclear weapons, terrorism, and security, Kerry Herron adn Hank Jenkins-Smith, Published by the University of Pittsburgh Press, 2006

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Another interesting aspect involves the relative trends in these two measures. In aggregate and across the entire survey period, the perceived difference in importance is modes!. Roughly 30 percent believe nuclear deterrence has become less important, 45 percent see no change, and 25 percent think deterrence has actually increased in importance since the Cold War. Over the period of our surveys, however, public opinion shifts noticeabl y. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)In 1995, respondents are roughly evenly divided on the question of whether deterrence has declined or increased in importance compared to the Cold War period(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) (28 percent to 23 percent). (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)By 2003, the balance shifts to 36 percent believing deterrence is less important now compared to only 21 percent who think deterrence is more important now. This shift is statist ically significant(%%) (chi-square p  .001). Thus, (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)public views of the relative value of nuclear deterrence are evolving,(%%) with perceptions of its importance for preventing nuclear conflict during the Cold War increasing retrospectively, while (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)perceptions of its contemporary importance are (%%)relatively (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)lower(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)and trending in the opposite direction.

