&#xD;
Yes, today we all have our dance. We can all express ourselves.&#xD;
&#xD;
They’re in a double bind. Either there is no signpost by which we can interpret good dancing from bad dancing, or they are simply a new marker of what constitutes acceptability in a certain forum, turning the 1NC.**&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
**Either they are saying that their dancing is radical break with the squo, but then everything counts as dancing; walking, running, falling, moving,**&#xD;
&#xD;
**or** &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
**Your dancing becomes the new standard of what dance is, and becomes as routinized and perfected and as alienated from criticism as the nutcracker.**&#xD;
&#xD;
&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
**Additionally, racism isnt anything that is based in biology or genetics but an arbitrary concept that we have imbed with meaning. While neither Baudrillard or me and stroud belive that means race isnt important, we think that the better response to people who are racist isnt to play by their rules and accept their terms of “a good relation with difference”. Instead, we would rather respond like muslim immigrants in france who brunt down schools, hospitals, and other things given to them by the French government as reparation for earlier injustices. We would respond like Gilmore, who was put on death row and instead of allowing the anti-capital punishment coalition to protest his execution, preferred to be executed. The aff is a withdrawl from the system writ large, and the neg is the insistence that we can have an authentic and proper relation to difference.** &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)**Baudrillard 2004**(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; &amp;#34; %) jean, undefeated, undisputed, know for his wisdom, compassion, and relentless determination to get paid, intelligence of evil or the lucidity pact&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Differences mean regulated exchange (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %). But what is it that introduces disorder into exchange? What is it that cannot be negotiated over? What is it that has no place in the contract, or in the structural interaction of differences? What is founded on the impossibility of exchange? (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Wherever exchange is impossible, (%%)what (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)we encounter (%%)is (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)terror. (%%)Any (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)radical otherness (%%)at all (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)is (%%)thus (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)the epicentre of a terror:(%%) the terror that such otherness holds, by virtue of its very existence, for the normal world. And the terror that this world exercises upon that otherness in order to annihilate it.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Over recent centuries all forms of violent otherness have been incorporated, willingly or under threat of force, into a discourse of difference which simultaneously implies inclusion and exclusion, recognition and discrimination. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Childhood, lunacy, death, primitive societies - all have been categorized, integrated and absorbed as parts of a universal harmony.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Madness, once its exclusionary status had been revoked, was caught up in the far subtler toils of psychology. The dead, as soon as they were recognized in their identity as such, were banished to outlying cemeteries - kept at such a distance that the face of death itself was lost. As for Indians, their right to exist was no sooner accorded them than they were confined to reservations. These are the vicissitudes of a logic of difference. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Racism(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)does not exist so long as the other remains Other, so long as the Stranger remains foreign. It comes into existence when the other becomes merely (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)different - that is to say, (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)dangerously similar. This is (%%)the moment (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)when the inclination to keep the other at a distance comes into being.(%%) &amp;#39;We may assume&amp;#39;, wrote Victor Segalen, &amp;#39;that fundamental differences will never resolve themselves into a truly seamless and unpatched fabric; increasing unity, falling (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)barriers and great reductions in real distance must (%%)of themselves (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)compensate (%%)somewhere (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)by (%%)means of (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)new partitions and unanticipated gaps(%%):(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Racism is one such &amp;#39;new partition&amp;#39; . An abreaction to the psychodrama of difference: a response to the phantasy of - and obsession with - becoming &amp;#39;other&amp;#39; . A way out of the psychodrama of perpetual introj ection and rej ection of the other. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)So intolerable is this introjection of differences, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)in fact, (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)that the other must be exorcized (%%)at all costs (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)by making the differences materially manifest(%%). The (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)biological claims of racism are without foundation but, by making the racial reference clear, racism does reveal the logical temptation at the heart of every structural system: (%%)the temptation (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)to fetishize difference(%%).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) But differential systems can never achieve equilibrium: differences oscillate constantly between absolute highs and absolute lows. When it comes to the management of otherness and difference, the idea of a well-tempered balance is strictly utopian. Inasmuch as the humanist logic of difference is in some sense a universal simulation (one which culminates in the absurdity of a &amp;#39;right to difference&amp;#39;), it leads directly, for all its benevolence, to that other desperate hallucination of difference known as racism. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)As differences and the cult of differences continue to grow, another, unprecedented kind of violence, anomalous and inaccessible to critical rationality, grows even faster. Segalen&amp;#39;s &amp;#39;unanticipated gaps&amp;#39; are not simply new differences: (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)what springs up (%%)in order to combat the total homogenization of the world (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)is (%%)the Alien - monstrous metaphor for (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)the corpse-like, viral Other(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %): the compound form of all the varieties of otherness done to death by our system. This is a racism which, for lack of any biological underpinning, seizes on the very slightest variations in the order of signs; a racism which quickly takes on a viral and automatic character, and perpetuates itself while revelling in a generalized semiotics . (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)And this racism can never be countered by any humanism of difference, for the simple reason that it is itself the virus of difference. Sermonizing on the internalization of the other and the introjection of differences can never resolve the problem of the monstrous forms of otherness, because these forms are the product, precisely, of this selfsame obsessional differentiation, this selfsame obsessional dialectic of ego and other. (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Herein lies the (%%)whole (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)weakness of (%%)those &amp;#39;dialectical&amp;#39; (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)theories (%%)of otherness (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)which aspire to promote the proper use of difference.(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)For if racism in its viral, immanent, current and definitive form proves anything, it is that there is no such thing as the proper use of difference(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) . This is why it may also be said that the critique of racism is subs tantially finished - just as Marx said that the critique of religion was substantially finished. Once the vacuousness of the metaphysical account of religion had been demonstrated, religion was supposed to disappear as the conditions of a more advanced mode of production became operative. Likewise, once the vacuousness of the biological theory of races has been demonstrated, racism is supposed to disappear as the conditions of a more advanced universal intermixture of differences become operative . But what if religion, for example, contrary to Marx&amp;#39; s predictions, had lost its metaphysical and transcendent form only to become an immanent force and fragment into countless ideological and practical variants under the conditions of a religious revival drawing sustenance from the progress of the very social order that was expected to eradicate even the memory of religion? For the signs of just such a turn of events are all around us today. And much the same goes for racism, which has also become an immanent, viral and everyday reality. The fact is (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)that the &amp;#39;scientific&amp;#39; and rational critique of racism is a purely formal one, which demolishes the argument from biology but remains caught in the racist trap because it addresses a biological illusion only, and fails to deal with biology itself qua illusion(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %). Similarly, (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)the (%%)political and (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)ideological critique of racism is purely formal in that it tackles the racist obsession with difference without tackling difference itself qua illusion. It (%%)thus itself (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)becomes an illusion of criticism, (%%)bearing on nothing, (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)and (%%)in the end (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)racism turns out to (%%)have (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)survived critique by rationalism j ust as (%%)deftly as (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)religion survived critique by materialism(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)- which is why all such critiques are indeed substantially finished . There is no such thing as the proper use of difference - a fact revealed not only by racism itself but also by all anti-racist and humanitarian efforts to promote and protect differences. Humanitarian ecumenism, the ecumenism of differences, is in a cul-de-sac: the cul-de-sac of the concept of the universal itself. The most recent illustration of this, in France, was the brouhaha over the wearing of headscarves for religious reasons by North African schoolgirls. All the rational arguments mustered in this connection turned out to be nothing but hypocritical attempts to get rid of the simple fact that no solution is to be found in any moral or political theory of difference. It is difference itself that is a reversible illusion. We are the ones who brought difference to the four corners of the earth: that it should now be returned to us in unrecognizable, Islamic, fundamentalist and irreducible forms is no bad thing. The guilt we feel in this connection assumes gigantic proportions . Not long ago the organization Medecins Sans Frontieres became aware that the medical supplies it had been distributing in Afghanistan were being resold rather than used directly by their recipients. This precipitated a crisis of conscience for the programme&amp;#39; s organizers . Should donations be discontinued, or should this immoral and irregular commerce be tolerated out of respect for &amp;#39;cultural differences&amp;#39;? After much soul-searching it was decided to sacrifice Western values on the altar of difference, and continue to underwrite the black market in medicines. Humanisme oblige. Another charming illustration of the confusion besetting our humanitarians concerns X, posted to the Sudan to study &amp;#39;the communications needs of Sudanese peoples&amp;#39; . Seemingly, the Sudanese did not know how to communicate. But they were certainly hungry, and needed to learn how to grow sorghum. Sending agronomists being too expensive a prospect, the decision had been taken to teach by videocassette. The time had come for the Sudanese to join the communications revolution: sorghum via audio and video. No hook-up, no eat. It was not long before towns and villages were crammed with VCRs. A little longer, and the local mafia created a lucrative market for itself in pornographic videotapes which held a distinctly greater interest for the populace than educational cassettes on sorghum cultivation. Porno-SorghoVideo : The Same Struggle!&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
**All movements to speak up and out against systems of oppression do not see they are moving directly in the direction that the system wants you to; you are aiming you criticism at reform instead of complete overhaul, which means you will never crystalize as a challenge to power, but something for it to accommodate**&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoFootnoteText&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;cite&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-bidi&amp;#34; %)**Baudrillard in 1981**(%%) ((% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)Jean, “Simulacra and Simulation” p. 84-86(%%))&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;card&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:0in;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)With one caution.  (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)We are face to face with this system in a (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %)double situation (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)and insoluble double bind(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)– exactly (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)like children faced with the(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)demands of the (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)adult world(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %). (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Children are (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %)simultaneously (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)required to constitute themselves as autonomous subjects, responsible, free and (%%)conscious, and to constitute them selves (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)as submissive, inert, obedient, conforming objects(%%).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %)The child resists on all levels, and to a contradictory demand he responds with a double strategy;(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %)To the demand of being an object  he opposes all the practices of disobedience, of revolt, of emancipation(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %); in short, a total claim to subjecthood. To the demand of being a subject he opposes, just as obstinately, and efficaciously, an object&amp;#39;s resistance, that is to say, exactly the opposite: childishness, hyperconformism, total dependence, passivity, idiocy: Neither strategy has more objective value than the other. The (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)subject-resistance is (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %)today unilaterally (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)valorized(%%) and viewed as positive-(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)just as (%%)in the political sphere (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)only the practices of freedom, emancipation, expression, and the constitution of a political subject are seen as valuable (%%)and subversive. (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)But this is to ignore (%%)the equal, and without a doubt superior, impact of all the (% style=&amp;#34;background: lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)object practices, of the renunciation of the subject position (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)and of meaning-precisely the practices of the masses-(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)that we bury under(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)the derisory(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)terms (%%)of alienation and (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)passivity(%%). The (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)liberating practices(%%) respond to one of the aspects of the system, to the constant ultimatum we are given to constitute ourselves as pure objects, but (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)they (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 12pt; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)do(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) not (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)respond(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %) at all (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)to the(%%) other (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)demand,(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %) that (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)of constituting ourselves as subjects, of liberating ourselves, expressing ourselves at whatever cost, of voting, producing, deciding, speaking, participating, playing the game - a form of blackmail(%%) and ultimatum just as serious as the other, (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)even more serious today(%%). (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)To a system whose argument is oppression and repression, the strategic resistance is the liberating claim of subjecthood. But this strategy is(%%) more reflective of the earlier phase of the system, and even if we are still confronted with it, it (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)is no longer the strategic terrain: the current argument of the system is to maximize speech, the maximum production of meaning. Thus the strategic resistance is that of the refusal of meaning and of the spoken word-or of the hyperconformist simulation of the very mechanisms of the system,(%%) which is a form of refusal and of non- reception(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %). It is the strategy of the masses: it is equivalent to(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)re-turning to the system its own logic by doubling it, to reflecting meaning, like a mirror, without absorbing it(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) This strategy (if one can still speak of strategy) prevails today, because it was ushered in by that phase of the system which prevails. To choose the wrong strategy is a serious matter. (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)All the movements that only play on liberation, emancipation, on the resurrection of a subject(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) of history, of the group, (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %)of the word based on (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)&amp;#34;consciousness raising,&amp;#34; indeed a &amp;#34;raising of the unconscious&amp;#34; of subjects and of the masses,(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)do not see that they are going in the direction of the system, whose imperative today is precisely the overproduction and regeneration of meaning and of speech(%%).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
**Instead, when they make arguments about how we always have to answer to our privilege, and speak from our subject location, this makes us slaves to our identity which is the worst form of oppression**&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)**Baudrillard**(%%)** explains in 2001**.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)To be able to disobey moral rules and laws(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %), to be able to disobey others, is a mark of freedom.  But the ability to disobey oneself marks the highest stage of freedom.  Obeying one’s own will is an even worse vice than being enslaved to one’s passions.  It is certainly worse than enslavement to the will of others.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)  And (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)it is,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)indeed, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)those who submit themselves mercilessly to their own decisions who fill the greater part of the authoritarian ranks, alleging sacrifice on their own part to impose even greater sacrifices on others. Each stage of servitude is both more subtle and worse than the one which precedes it.  Involuntary servitude(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), the servitude of the slave, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)is overt violence(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %).  (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Voluntary servitude is a violence consented to:(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)a freedom to will, but not the will to be free.  (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Last comes(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)voluntary self-servitude or (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)enslavement to one’s own will: the individual possesses the faculty to will, but is no longer free in respect of it.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)  (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)He is the automatic agent of that faculty.  (%%)He is the serf to no master but himself(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)**We’ll borrow from the magnetic fields and argue: perm-nothing matters when we’re dancing.**&#xD;
&#xD;
&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) </headline></objectSummary><objectSummary><link rel="http://www.xwiki.org/rel/object" href="http://opencaselist.paperlessdebate.com/xwiki/rest/wikis/opencaselist/spaces/Texas-San%20Antonio/pages/nerison-stroud%20Aff/objects/Admin.EntryClass/7"/><link rel="http://www.xwiki.org/rel/properties" href="http://opencaselist.paperlessdebate.com/xwiki/rest/wikis/opencaselist/spaces/Texas-San%20Antonio/pages/nerison-stroud%20Aff/objects/Admin.EntryClass/7/properties"/><id>opencaselist:Texas-San Antonio.nerison-stroud Aff:d431e2c6-81e9-41d3-ad88-b94dbd6f4c5a</id><guid>d431e2c6-81e9-41d3-ad88-b94dbd6f4c5a</guid><pageId>opencaselist:Texas-San Antonio.nerison-stroud Aff</pageId><wiki>opencaselist</wiki><space>Texas-San Antonio</space><pageName>nerison-stroud Aff</pageName><className>Admin.EntryClass</className><number>7</number><headline>== AT: Transhumanism ==

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNoSpacing&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt&amp;#34; %)__ __

==== Perm: Do Both. ====

(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 13.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Kinsella 2007 (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)(William J, “Heidegger and Being at the Hanford Reservation: Standing Reserve, Enframing, and Environmental (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-language:EN-US&amp;#34; %)Communication Theory.” //Environmental Communication// - Vol. 1, No. 2, November 2007, pp. 194**_**217)


(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNoSpacing&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)Additionally, and(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.5pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)consistent with(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.5pt;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)Rogers’ search for(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.5pt; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)a ‘‘transhuman’’ approach, Heidegger’s phenomenology enables a powerful critique of humanism.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.5pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)By analogy with models of ‘‘bounded rationality’’ (March and Simon, 1958) and ‘‘bounded emotionality’’ (Mumby and Putnam, 1992) in organizational theory, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)such an approach might take the form of a ‘‘bounded constitutive’’ model of communication(%%).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %) In that model, humans have substantial power to constitute the world and its meanings, but that power is constrained by, and must be responsible to, the transcendental facticity of nature. Below, I outline the directions such a model might take, using as foundations Heidegger’s critique of humanism, the notion of ‘‘care’’ that emerges in his critique of enframing, and a recent philosophical reading of his phenomenology as a form of ‘‘ontic realism’’ (Carman, 2003, pp. 44ff). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Consistent with Rogers’ liberatory goals, such an approach opens up the discursive space for a broader range of voices and arguments in public environmental discourse, environmental conflict, and environmental policy debate.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.5pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)In that spirit, I now examine some key ideas from Heidegger’s phenomenology and their potential for integrating concerns for nature, as conceptualized in radical ecology, with concerns for human welfare and emancipation.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.5pt&amp;#34; %) 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 </headline></objectSummary><objectSummary><link rel="http://www.xwiki.org/rel/object" href="http://opencaselist.paperlessdebate.com/xwiki/rest/wikis/opencaselist/spaces/Texas-San%20Antonio/pages/nerison-stroud%20Aff/objects/Admin.EntryClass/8"/><link rel="http://www.xwiki.org/rel/properties" href="http://opencaselist.paperlessdebate.com/xwiki/rest/wikis/opencaselist/spaces/Texas-San%20Antonio/pages/nerison-stroud%20Aff/objects/Admin.EntryClass/8/properties"/><id>opencaselist:Texas-San Antonio.nerison-stroud Aff:d350ef85-083e-4bc2-9f01-f27e89606fb9</id><guid>d350ef85-083e-4bc2-9f01-f27e89606fb9</guid><pageId>opencaselist:Texas-San Antonio.nerison-stroud Aff</pageId><wiki>opencaselist</wiki><space>Texas-San Antonio</space><pageName>nerison-stroud Aff</pageName><className>Admin.EntryClass</className><number>8</number><headline>(% style=&amp;#34;mso-element:para-border-div;border:solid windowtext 3.0pt; padding:1.0pt 4.0pt 1.0pt 4.0pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(((&#xD;
= AT: Natives =&#xD;
)))&#xD;
&#xD;
==== Giving the land back continues the oppression of indigenous peoples; this humanist logic of difference is already the way that we have waged cultural genocide against these peoples, and denies them the revenge they are beginning to take upon us. ====&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Jean (% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Baudrillard(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (Paris, France). ISSN: 1705-6411 Volume 3, Number 1 (January (% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)2006(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)) The Melodrama of Difference (Or, The Revenge of the Colonized). Oh yeah, Baudrillard is totally an indian/native studies BALLER.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Does the other exist for the Savage or the Primitive? Some relationships are asymmetrical: (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)the one may be the other for the other without this implying that the other is the other for the one(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %). I may be other for him even though he is not the other for me. The Alakaluf of Tierra del Fuego were wiped out without ever having sought to understand the Whites,(%%) without ever even speaking to them or negotiating with them. They called themselves &amp;#39;Men&amp;#39; - and there were no others. In their eyes the (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Whites were not even different: they were unintelligible. They evinced no surprise at the newcomers&amp;#39; vast wealth and amazing technology.(%%) Despite three centuries of contact, (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)the Alakaluf adopted not a single Western technique(%%), continuing, for instance, to row around in skiffs. The Whites might oppress and slaughter them, but it was for all the world as if they did not exist. (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)The Alakaluf were to be annihilated without conceding anything of their otherness. They would never be assimilated(%%) - indeed, they would never even reach the stage of difference. They would (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)perish without ever allowing the Whites the privilege of recognizing them as different(%%). The Alakaluf were simply irrecuperable. (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)For the Whites(%%), nevertheless, they were 1 &amp;#39;others&amp;#39; - beings that (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)were different yet still human, or at least human enough to be evangelized, exploited, and killed(%%).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) As a sovereign people the Alakaluf called themselves &amp;#39;Men&amp;#39;. Then the Whites applied to them the name that they had originally applied to the Whites: &amp;#39;Foreigners&amp;#39;. They eventually came to refer to themselves as &amp;#39;foreigners&amp;#39; in their own language. In later times they called themselves &amp;#39;Alakaluf&amp;#39; - the only word that they still pronounced in front of Whites, meaning &amp;#39;Give, give&amp;#39;. They thus ended up with a designation connoting the mendacity to which they had been reduced. First, then, they were themselves, then strangers to themselves, and finally absent from themselves: three names reflecting three stages of their extermination. Naturally (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)their murder is to be attributed to those who possess the universalizing vision, those who manipulate otherness for their own profit.(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) In their singularity, which could not even conceive of the Other, the Alakaluf were inevitably vanquished. (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)But who can say that the elimination of this singularity will not turn out(%%), in the long run,(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) to be fatal (%%)for the Whites too? Who can say that radical foreignness will not have its revenge - that, (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)though effectively conjured away by colonial humanism, it will not return in the form of a virus(%%) in the bloodstream of the Whites, dooming them to disappear themselves one day in much the same way as the Alakaluf. Everything is subservient to the system, yet at the same time escapes its control. Those (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)groups around the world who adopt the Western lifestyle never really identify with it, and indeed are secretly contemptuous of it. (%%)They remain excentric with respect to this value system. (% style=&amp;#34;background: lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Their way of assimilating(%%), of often (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)being more fanatical in their observance of Western manners than Westerners themselves, has an obviously parodic(%%), aping (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)quality(%%): they are engaged in a sort of bricolage with the broken bits and pieces of the Enlightenment, of &amp;#39;progress&amp;#39;. (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Even when they negotiate or ally themselves with the West, they continue to believe that their own way is fundamentally the right one(%%). Perhaps, like the Alakalut these groups will disappear without ever having taken the Whites seriously. (For our part we take them very seriously indeed, whether our aim is to assimilate them or destroy them: they are even fast becoming the crucial - negative - reference point of our whole value system.) The (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Whites will perhaps themselves disappear one day without ever having understood that their whiteness is merely the result of the promiscuity and confusion of all races and cultures(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), just as the whiteness of white light is simply the resolution of the melodrama of all colours. And just as colours become comparable amongst themselves only when they are measured against a universal scale of wavelengths, so cultures become comparable only when they are set against a structural scale of differences. But there is a double standard here, for it is only for Western culture that other cultures are different. For those other cultures themselves, Whites are not even different - they are non-existent, phantoms from another world. Outward conversion to Western ways invariably conceals inward scoffing at Western hegemony. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)One is put in mind of those Dogons who made up dreams to humour their psychoanalysts and then offered these dreams to the analysts as gifts.(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) Once we despised other cultures; now we respect them. They do not respect our culture, however; they feel nothing but an immense condescension for it. (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)We may have won the right by conquest to exploit and subjugate these cultures, but they have offered themselves the luxury of mystifying us.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) The strangest feeling one is left with after reading Bruce Chatwin&amp;#39;s Songlines is a lingering perplexity about the reality of the &amp;#39;lines&amp;#39; themselves: do these poetic and musical itineraries, these songs, this &amp;#39;dreamtime&amp;#39;, really exist or not? In all these accounts there is a hint of mystification; a kind of mythic optical illusion seems to be operating. It is as though the Aboriginals were fobbing us off. While unveiling the profoundest and most authentic of truths (the Austral myth at its most mysterious), they also play up the most modern and hypothetical of considerations: the irresolvability of any narrative, absolute doubt as to the origins. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)For us to believe these fabulous things, we need to feel that they themselves believe them. But these Aboriginals seem to take a mischievous pleasure in being allusive and evasive.(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)They give a few clues, but never tell us the rules of the game, and one cannot help getting the impression that they are improvising, pandering to our phantasies, but withholding any reassurance that what they are telling us is true. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)This is doubtless their way of keeping their secrets while at the same time poking fun at us(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) - for in the end we are the only people who want to believe these tales. (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)The Aboriginals&amp;#39; secret resides not in what they omit to say(%%), however, (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)but entirely within the thread, within the indecipherable filigree of the narrative;(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)we are confronted by an ironic form here, by a mythology of appearances. And in the manipulation of this form the Aboriginals are far more adept than we are. We Whites are liable to remain mystified for a good while yet. The simulation of Western values is universal once one gets beyond the boundaries of our culture. Is it not true, though, that in our heart of hearts we ourselves, who are neither Alakaluf nor Aboriginal, neither Dogon nor Arab, fail signally to take our own values seriously? Do we not embrace them with the same affectation and inner unconcern - and are we not ourselves equally unimpressed by all our shows of force, all our technological and ideological pretensions? Nevertheless, it will be a long time before the utopian abstraction of our universal vision of differences is demolished in our own eyes, whereas all other cultures have already given their own response - namely, universal indifference(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %). It is not even remotely a matter of rehabilitating the Aboriginals, or finding them a place in the chorus of human rights, for their revenge lies elsewhere. It lies in their power to destabilize Western rule.(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) It lies in (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)their phantom presence, their viral, spectral presence in the synapses of our brains, in the circuitry of our rocketship, as &amp;#39;Alien&amp;#39;; in the way in which the Whites have caught the virus of origins, of Indianness,(%%) of Aboriginality, of Patagonicity. We murdered all this, but now it infects our blood, into which it has been inexorably transfused and infiltrated. (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)The revenge of the colonized is in no sense the reappropriation by Indians or Aboriginals of their lands, privileges or autonomy: that is our victory. (%%)Rather, that (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)revenge may be seen in the way in which the Whites have been (%%)mysteriously (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)made aware of the disarray of their own culture, (%%)the way in which they have been overwhelmed by an ancestral torpor and are now succumbing little by little to the grip of &amp;#39;dream time&amp;#39;. (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)This reversal is a (%%)worldwide (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)phenomenon. It is now becoming clear that everything we once thought dead and buried, everything we thought left behind for ever by the ineluctable march of universal progress, is not dead at all, but on the contrary likely to return(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) - not as some archaic or nostalgic vestige (all our indefatigable museumification notwithstanding), but with a vehemence and a virulence that are modern in every sense - and to reach the very heart of our ultrasophisticated but ultra-vulnerable systems, which it will easily convulse from within without mounting a frontal attack. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Such is the destiny of radical otherness - a destiny that no homily of reconciliation and no apologia for difference is going to alter(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 </headline></objectSummary><objectSummary><link rel="http://www.xwiki.org/rel/object" href="http://opencaselist.paperlessdebate.com/xwiki/rest/wikis/opencaselist/spaces/Texas-San%20Antonio/pages/nerison-stroud%20Aff/objects/Admin.EntryClass/9"/><link rel="http://www.xwiki.org/rel/properties" href="http://opencaselist.paperlessdebate.com/xwiki/rest/wikis/opencaselist/spaces/Texas-San%20Antonio/pages/nerison-stroud%20Aff/objects/Admin.EntryClass/9/properties"/><id>opencaselist:Texas-San Antonio.nerison-stroud Aff:d2043481-36c6-4f1d-9af3-338901e949b3</id><guid>d2043481-36c6-4f1d-9af3-338901e949b3</guid><pageId>opencaselist:Texas-San Antonio.nerison-stroud Aff</pageId><wiki>opencaselist</wiki><space>Texas-San Antonio</space><pageName>nerison-stroud Aff</pageName><className>Admin.EntryClass</className><number>9</number><headline>(% style=&amp;#34;mso-element:para-border-div;border:solid windowtext 3.0pt; padding:1.0pt 4.0pt 1.0pt 4.0pt&amp;#34; %)
